# --- ACE OF CUPS ---

:: TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups
@if cards[0].reversed:
    The Ace of Cups — reversed. A cup overturned. Feelings locked inside, unexpressed, a wellspring that's been stopped.

    Ellen looks at the inverted cup. "Something spilled?" she asks, half-joking. Not really joking.

    Scout tilts his head — the way he does when a song changes key and he's trying to feel whether it went up or down before his theory brain can name the interval. This card interests him. He's not sure why yet.

    Mal writes something in the composition notebook. A single word, underlined. You can't see what it is from here, but Mal writing things down during a reading means they've identified a thread they don't want to lose.

    Delphi is watching Ellen's hands. Not the card — Ellen's hands. They're clasped in her lap and the knuckles are white and Delphi sees that and her expression does something subtle and warm, like a song resolving to the tonic.

    + ["Reversed, this card often means an emotion that got *stuck* — something you felt so deeply it never fully processed. You keep returning to this memory because there's a feeling in it that never got to finish."] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_R_Empathic
    + ["The Ace reversed can mean a blocked emotional channel. Something you can't express, or haven't allowed yourself to. This search might be carrying an emotion you haven't found another outlet for — like a song stuck on repeat because you never let it play to the end."] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_R_Reframing
    + ["Sometimes this card reversed means you're afraid to feel what finding it would bring up."] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_R_Practical
    + ["Reversed Ace of Cups means blocked emotions. You might want to consider talking to someone about your grief."] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_R_Blunt
@else:
    The Ace of Cups. A single cup, overflowing. Water cascading down in five streams, lilies blooming where it falls. The hand of something larger offering the first feeling, the original feeling, the one that came before you had a name for it.

    Ellen stares at the overflow. The excess. Something about the image of *too much feeling to hold* has caught her, the way a hook catches in a song before you understand the lyrics.

    Scout tilts his head — the way he does when a song changes key and he's trying to feel whether it went up or down before his theory brain can name the interval. This card interests him. He's not sure why yet.

    Mal writes something in the composition notebook. A single word, underlined. You can't see what it is, but Mal writing things down during a reading means they've identified a thread they don't want to lose. They're building Ellen's index entry in real time.

    Delphi is watching Ellen's hands. Not the card — Ellen's hands. They're clasped in her lap and the knuckles are white and Delphi sees that and her expression does something subtle and warm, like a song resolving to the tonic. She knows where this is going.

    + ["The Ace of Cups is a first feeling. The original recording — not the remaster, not the remix, not the cover version you heard later. The demo tape. The first take. Your mom put a record on and something in you *opened* — some channel you didn't have before — and you've been listening through it ever since."] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_U_Poetic
    + ["There's a term in audio engineering — 'reference track.' The recording you compare everything else against. It sets the standard. This card says that night in the kitchen *became* your reference track for feeling. Not just for music — for all feeling."] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_U_Reframing
    + ["This card is about capacity. Before that night, you felt things the way kids feel things — big but formless. That record taught you that feelings could have *structure.* A beginning, a middle, a part that breaks you open, a part that puts you back together. Your mom didn't just play you a song. She handed you the blueprint for how to feel."] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_U_Empathic
    + ["This card is about emotions and new feelings. What emotions come up when you think about this record?"] -> TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_U_Vague
@endif

# Ace of Cups — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session1.P1_AceCups_U_Poetic
"The Ace of Cups is a first feeling. The original recording — not the remaster, not the remix, not the cover version you heard later and thought was better because you were older. The demo tape. The first take."

You let that settle.

"Your mom put a record on and something in you *opened* — some channel you didn't have before — and you've been listening through it ever since. Every song that's ever made you cry is a callback to that first take."

Ellen goes still. Then, quietly, with the precise voice of someone who has just understood something:

"I think that's the first song that ever made me cry. And I wasn't crying because of the music. I was crying because my mom was crying, and I understood for the first time that she had a whole inner life I couldn't see."

The reading nook goes very quiet. The colored light from the stained glass moves slowly across Ellen's hands.

"I was eleven and I realized my mother was a *person.* Not just my mom. A whole person with feelings I couldn't access. And that was enormous. And terrifying. And beautiful."

Scout, leaning against the vinyl bins, is holding a record sleeve very tightly and not blinking.

