# --- SEVEN OF CUPS ---

:: TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups
@if cards[2].reversed:
    The Seven of Cups — reversed. The fantasies clearing. A moment of focus cutting through the noise.

    Scout straightens up. Reversed Seven feels like the moment the mix clears and you can hear each instrument separately.

    Mal nods once. Data resolving into pattern.

    Delphi is already looking at Ellen, not the card. She knows what's coming.

    + ["Reversed, this card says you're *finally* hearing clearly. The noise is fading — all the versions, all the maybes — and what's left is the real thing. The block was never the record. It was the hundred versions of the record you'd built around it."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_R_Empathic
    + ["This reversal means you're ready to choose. You've been drowning in possibilities and this card says you're coming up for air. The block is dissolving on its own."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_R_Reframing
    + ["Seven of Cups reversed means things are becoming clearer. Good sign."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_R_Practical
    + ["The confusion is clearing. You should be able to find what you need."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_R_Vague
@else:
    The Seven of Cups. Seven cups floating in clouds, each holding something different — castle, jewels, snake, wreath, dragon, ghost, a veiled shining figure. Choices. Illusions. Fantasy.

    Scout whistles low. He knows this card — the overwhelming wall of sound when you're trying to isolate one instrument.

    Mal's eyes flick to Ellen, then to the card, then to the deep shelves. Triangulating.

    Delphi sips her tea. Steady. Waiting.

    + ["The Seven of Cups is about having too many possibilities and not being able to choose. Every time you revisit the memory, it shifts. Were the strings really strings, or was it a guitar? Was the voice low or just warm? Was the song slow or did grief slow it down in your memory? You've got seven versions and you're trying to Shazam all of them at once."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_U_Reframing
    + ["This card says the block is *imagination.* Your memory is creative — you're a writer, it's what you *do* — and it's been adding to this record for twenty years. You're not looking for one song anymore. You're looking for a song that only exists in you."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_U_Poetic
    + ["Seven of Cups can mean being lost in fantasy. You might be chasing an idealization rather than a real recording."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_U_Practical
    + ["This card means confusion and too many options. Try narrowing your search criteria."] -> TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_U_Vague
@endif

# Seven of Cups — Upright interpretations

:: TheKind.Session1.P3_SevenCups_U_Reframing
"The Seven of Cups is about having too many possibilities and not being able to choose. Every time you revisit the memory, it shifts a little. Were the strings really strings, or was it a guitar? Was the voice low or just warm? Was the song slow or did grief slow it down in your memory?"

Ellen almost laughs. The first real laugh of the session.

"Oh god, yes. I have a *spreadsheet.* With columns for 'definitely remember' and 'might be adding' and 'possibly from a different song entirely.'"

From the book stacks, Mal's voice, quiet and deadpan: "I'd like to see that spreadsheet."

Ellen startles — she didn't know anyone was listening from back there — and then laughs again, for real this time. The tension in the reading nook drops three degrees.

